## **Create a New Character** 

*NOTE: Most of this process will be automated in the future.* 

* At the top of the page in the viewport window select the tab Modding-\> Open Steam Workshop UI   
* Select New button, this will make a new character mod info, do some automatic folder creation, as well as actually make the mod on the workshop   
* You will know this worked correctly when you see the content folder field get auto-populated and you are given an Update Handle. As well you should be able to see your mod on the Steam Workshop   
* **IMPORTANT:** Go to your Mod on the Steam Workshop and Subscribe to it, otherwise you won’t be able to load it in the future for testing ![][image1]  
* Right-click on a ***CD\_ blueprint*** contained in another character’s folder  
  * Example:  
    * Navigate to **Characters/Clairen**   
    * Right-click **CD\_Clairen**   
* Scripted Asset Actions \-\> Create New Character![][image2]


* Give the character a name   
* Click OK 


  ![][image3]


  *The folder for the new character will be placed in Content/Characters* 


  

* In the editor, go into the new folder and move its contents into ModContent/\[YourModID\]![][image4]

  ![][image5]

* Open the **CD\_** file (in this example, **CD\_Armando**)   
* Click “**Class Settings**“  
* Change the **Parent Class** to **RivalsLuaCharacterData** 

  ![][image6]

* Click **Class Defaults** (next to Class Settings) 

   ![][image7]

* Change the **Animations Directory** and **Attack Data Directory** in the **CD\_** file to start with **…/Game/ModContent/\[ModID\]/UnrealAssets**

 ![][image8]![][image9] 

* Open the **Char\_** file (in this example, Char\_Arm)   
* Click **Class Settings**   
* Change the **Parent Class** to **RivalsLuaCharacterDefinition**

 ![][image10]

### **Create Character Lua File** 

* Copy and paste **Resources/CharacterScriptTemplate.lua** into your **…/ModContent/\[ModID\]/Scripts** folder, and then rename the copy to what you want  
* Edit the script and replace **@CharacterName** with the name of your character.   
  * Example: If your character’s name is Armando, then replace everywhere **@CharacterName** appears in the script with **Armando**   
    * Also remove the @ symbol  
* Open the **CD\_** asset (CD\_Armando for example).   
* Select **Class Defaults** and expand the **Lua section**   
* Set the **Lua Script Path** to the path to your script,   
  * Starting from the **ModID: \[ModID\]/Scripts/\[ScriptName\].lua**   
* Set the **MetatableName** to the character name you replaced **@CharacterName** with in the script   
  * In this case, set MetatableName to **Armando** 

 ![][image11]

*Do not try to play your character yet\!*

### **Create Victory Sequence Data** 

**IMPORTANT:** If you try to play your character now, your game will crash

**This is because you still need to set up a Victory Sequence Data asset** 

* To create one from scratch in the editor, navigate to   
  * **Content/ModContent/\[ModID\]/UnrealAssets/Skins/Default**, and create a folder called **VictorySequences**  
* Open the new **VictorySequences** folder you just created   
* Right-click in the empty space, then select **Miscellaneous \-\> Data Asset**   
  * The **first instance of Data Asset**, as there are several buttons with the same name  
     ![][image12]![][image13]

      
* In the class picker popup, search for “**Rivals Victory Sequence Data**”, and select it  
  ![][image14]

  ![][image15]

    
* Give the file a name   
  * A good practice is to prefix the name with part of your character’s name.   
  * Example: the Victory Sequence Data for Kragg’s default skin is **Kra\_Victory\_Default**

    ### **Hook up Victory Sequence to Character Definition** 

    The next step is to hook up your Victory Sequence Data in your character’s default skin definition

* Navigate to **Content/ModContent/\[ModID\]/UnrealAssets/Skins/Default/Data**  
* Open the **Skin\_** asset.   
* Click the dropdown next to **Victory Sequence Data** and select the Victory Sequence Data you just created in the previous section
